{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/what-are-hyper-spectral-images-a5de5d9fa91", "time": 1683001368.439287, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/what-are-hyper-spectral-images-a5de5d9fa91/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "What are Hyperspectral Images?. How are they different from the digital\u2026 | by Sarthak Panigrahi | Towards Data Science", "h1": "What are Hyperspectral Images?", "description": "The wall above sure looks very colourful and the mobile camera does a pretty awesome job to capture the same vivid colours for our eyes to witness\u2026 but there is a limit to what our eyes can perceive\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nanometre", "anchor_text": "nm", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "http://www.webexhibits.org/causesofcolor/17C.html", "anchor_text": "eyes of other animals", "paragraph_index": 6}, {"url": "https://www.e-education.psu.edu/geog480/node/494", "anchor_text": "remote sensing data", "paragraph_index": 8}, {"url": "https://www.vttresearch.com/media/news/specim%E2%80%99s-hyperspectral-camera-detects-counterfeit-medicine-and-traces-of-blood", "anchor_text": "Medical", "paragraph_index": 10}], "all_paragraphs": ["The wall above sure looks very colourful and the mobile camera does a pretty awesome job to capture the same vivid colours for our eyes to witness\u2026 but there is a limit to what our eyes can perceive and there may be aspects in the same image which neither our naked eye nor a mobile RGB camera can capture. This is where Hyperspectral Cameras come into play.", "In a way, digital images are just a bunch of numbers(but then again, doesn\u2019t that hold true for everything!?\ud83e\udd14). What gives these numbers a shape of an image are parameters defined on them to apply some constraints- like let\u2019s say, numbers being stacked in a row/column format, numbers having a particular range of values, etc.", "Binary Images:These are what we would otherwise call Black and White Images, as the words clearly scream to you- they consist of only 2 different numbers (zeros and ones), which corresponds to 2 different colours viz. black and white respectively. These numbers are saved as a 2-D matrix of n rows/ m columns format, where the 0\u2019s are black in colour and 1\u2019s are white in colour.", "Greyscale Images:They are much more informative as they mostly consist of 255 different numbers(let\u2019s say, from 0 to 255) to convey information; each number corresponds to the intensity of grey-value. In other words,", "Colour Images: Now, this is how our eyes(cone cells) perceive the environment around us, giving it a colourful rendering. Instead of a single greyscale image, we will be having 3 channels of red-scale, green-scale and blue-scale images. The combination of these three intensities will be perceived by our eyes as one of the many possible \u2018colours\u2019. So, it will have dimensions of :(n rows*m columns)*3 channels.", "As we know the different red,green and blue coloration is due to the fact that the reflected light from objects fall under separate wavelength ranges in the visible spectrum of the electromagnetic radiation[i.e. long wavelengths, peaking near 564\u2013580 nm (red); medium-wavelength, peaking near 534\u2013545 nm (green); and short-wavelength light, near 420\u2013440 nm (blue)]; this is all that our human eyes can perceive but there is a lot of wavelengths not covered by the visible spectrum that is easily missed/invisible to our eyes.", "These colours/features missed by human eyes may be relatively seen by the eyes of other animals- like they say, \u2018Color lies in the eyes of the beholder\u2019.", "Thanks to advancements in imaging technology, we can get information regarding the wavelengths beyond the visible spectrum and make sense of it. So, in a broad sense, spectral imaging is the parallel acquisition of spatial and their corresponding spectral information in an image space and their combination thereof. It is kind of similar to an RGB colour image, but it has a lot more channels and thereby poses a challenge to be visualized as a whole(but we still have all the data for our smart-machines to understand\ud83e\uddd0). For comprehension purposes, let\u2019s say we have a n band hyper-spectral image: it is simply n grey-scale images(each band capturing different light intensity data according to their wavelength values) stacked on top of each other over a contiguous wavelength range- giving us an image of dimension n rows* m columns* n bands.", "Prior to hyperspectral images, we also have multi-spectral images which are essentially n band images, but they aren\u2019t necessarily spread over a contiguous wavelength range and in terms of the number of bands- they have fewer bands as compared to any average hyper-spectral image. We get to see real-world multi-spectral images in the remote sensing data gathered from satellites.", "So, the image acquired from any HSI camera will be in the form of a hypercube, having n-dimensional image data which can be overwhelming at times. Thus, it is not uncommon to apply dimensional-reduction techniques to the same and have many other approaches to process the hypercube. Here, if we try to focus on a single hyper-pixel, we would be able to plot a continuous spectrum data for the same.", "It has applications in a plethora of fields ranging from Medical, Agricultural, Textiles to the automotive industry. HSI helps us to explore the unexplored, by visualizing information invisible to human eyes and finding a method to make sense of it.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fa5de5d9fa91&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&re